# Code Security

## Input And Query Safety
- Validate inputs at trust boundaries; prefer allowlists for constrained values.
- Use parameterized queries or safe ORM builders. Never concatenate user input into SQL or shell commands.
- Sanitize/escape output for the target context: HTML, JavaScript, SQL, logs, or filenames.

## Secrets
- Never hardcode passwords, API keys, tokens, or default credentials.
- Do not log secret values; log stable IDs or redacted summaries.

## Error Handling
- Do not expose stack traces, raw database errors, or internal paths to users.
- Return structured errors; log diagnostic context privately.

## Auth And Authorization
- Check authorization server-side for every privileged action.
- Do not rely on UI hiding or client-side checks for access control.
